{"key":"processedPost-8607541","value":{"id":8607541,"first":8602765,"last":18368299,"when":1215531007,"utime":"07/08/08 06:30 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>nonlinear said:</strong><br />RR, can you explain why PC with stopcock is called a sterilizer, and PC with a weight is called a PC?&nbsp; i understand how they are different, but why the name difference? </blockquote><br />A PC with a stopcock will produce a vacuum as it cools.&nbsp; Any materal inside will remain completely sterile until you open the unit, hopefully in front of a laminar flowhood.&nbsp; Note: New AA pressure cookers and sterilizers have a silly rubber overpressure plug that leaks when pressure reaches zero, preventing the formation of a vacuum.&nbsp; I solve this by placing a sheet or two of tyvek over the rubber plug, held down by a shotglass.&nbsp; Don't put the tyvek over the plug until the PC has cooled to below 15 psi though, as it's temperature sensitive.<br />RR","title":"Re: Save Some $$$$$ Pressure Cooker Tek"}}